# Lean bundle & performance

Prefer smaller downloads and fewer eager imports. Measure with `npm run build` / `npm run analyze` when changing deps or large UI.

## Icons

- Prefer `i-heroicons-*` (primary) or `i-lucide-*` (already allowed)
- **Do not** add new `@iconify-json/*` packages or new Iconify prefixes without removing an unused set
- Never install full `@iconify/json` or giant sets (e.g. material-symbols) for a few icons — swap to heroicons/lucide instead
- Keep `nuxt.config` `icon.serverBundle.collections` limited to collections we ship

## Imports & code splitting

```ts
// ❌ Eager load of a multi-thousand-line form on a list page
import PurchaseOrderForm from '~/components/purchaseOrders/PurchaseOrderForm.vue'

// ✅ Load only when the form is opened
const PurchaseOrderForm = defineAsyncComponent(
  () => import('~/components/purchaseOrders/PurchaseOrderForm.vue'),
)
```

- Heavy UI (forms, modals, editors, charts, PDF/excel): `defineAsyncComponent` or dynamic `import()`
- Heavy libs (`jspdf`, `html-to-image`, `write-excel-file`, `papaparse`, chart libs): dynamic `import()` at call site — never top-level in shared layouts/stores
- Do not add large packages to `vite.optimizeDeps.include` unless required for HMR correctness

## Assets & CSS

- Do not import whole icon/CSS catalogs for a few items (e.g. full `country-flag-icons/.../flags.css`) — import only needed modules/SVGs
- Avoid new global CSS that pulls large third-party sheets into every route

## Dependencies

- Before adding a dependency: prefer existing stack (Nuxt UI, dayjs, Dexie, Prisma)
- Reject “convenience” SDKs that duplicate server APIs or bloat the client
- Production: no sourcemaps unless debugging a release (`nitro.sourceMap` / `vite.build.sourcemap` stay off)
